    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the \"enchanted\" thing makes sense but why is it called \"spooky action at a distance\" though? like, what is actually happening that makes it so weird compared to just some regular connection between things?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was quite skeptical about this phenomenon. He found it strange because, in his view, nothing should be able to influence another thing instantly over a distance, as it would violate the speed limit set by the speed of light. It's like saying a message could be sent faster than a speeding dragon, which would be quite a surprise to anyone who believes in the normal rules of the world. In quantum entanglement, it's as if two goblins are whispering secrets to each other through a magical tunnel that allows them to share information instantly, defying the usual laws of the land. This \"spooky\" part is because it seems to break the very fabric of our understanding of how the universe works, like discovering a hidden passage in a castle that no one knew existed.",
